<!-- ============================================================
HLD GENERATION TEMPLATE — hld-template.md.tmpl
============================================================
HOW TO USE
1. Provide inputs alongside this template:
   - BRD (business requirements document)         [REQUIRED]
   - FRD / PRD (functional requirements)          [REQUIRED]
   - NFRs (nfr.md or stated targets)              [REQUIRED — if absent, generate ASSUMPTIONS and flag]
   - Business constraints (budget, timeline, mandated tech)  [RECOMMENDED]
   - Domain context (tenancy, regulatory scope, existing landscape)  [RECOMMENDED]
   - Role/team list                               [OPTIONAL]
   - Existing ADRs                                [OPTIONAL]
2. Prompt: "Use the HLD template. Fill it from the attached BRD and FRD.
   Follow all embedded generation rules."
3. The AI replaces every {{placeholder}}, deletes instruction comments,
   and deletes any section marked OMIT-IF-NOT-APPLICABLE that doesn't apply
   (recording the omission in §1.3).

GLOBAL GENERATION RULES (apply to every section)
R1  NO-INVENTION: every number (TPS, users, volumes, latency, retention,
    growth) must trace to an input document. If missing, create ASSUMPTION-nn
    in §13 with a stated default, reference it inline as "sized under
    ASSUMPTION-nn", and add it to §15 Open Questions if the design would
    change materially depending on the true value. NEVER invent a plausible
    figure.
R2  TRACE: every functional statement cites its source as [BRD-x], [FR-x],
    [NFR-x], or [ASSUMPTION-nn]. If you cannot cite it, don't write it.
R3  OWNERS: if no role list was provided, use the literal «OWNER-TBD» /
    «DATE-TBD». Never guess names, roles, or sprints.
R4  TIER A sections (marked below) use the full sub-structure: Purpose /
    Design Detail / Key Decisions / Alternatives / Risks / Validation /
    Downstream Implications / Open Questions. Budget 300–600 words + tables.
R5  TIER B sections use only Purpose / Content (+ Constraints if any).
    Budget 100–250 words. Do NOT add Alternatives tables to Tier B.
R6  HONEST ALTERNATIVES: each Tier A Alternatives table needs at least one
    genuinely viable option; the Cons of the SELECTED approach must be
    stated and carried into that section's Risks. A trade study where the
    winner sweeps every column is invalid.
R7  DIAGRAMS: every section describing structure or flow must reference a
    diagram at hld-<view>.drawio — either existing (state what to
    verify in it) or specified (type, required elements, target path).
R8  ANTI-GENERIC: banned phrases include "the system should be scalable",
    "security will be implemented", "integrates with external systems",
    "monitoring will be configured". Always state: WHAT scales, the sourced
    load figure, WHICH component absorbs it and how, WHAT failure mode is
    protected against, WHICH named control applies, WHICH integration
    pattern and why, and the SPECIFIC metric/threshold/alert that proves
    the design works.
R9  CONSOLIDATION: per-section Risks and Open Questions also roll up into
    §14 and §15. Assumptions live ONLY in §13 and are referenced inline.
R10 DECISIONS: every Tier A Key Decision links an ADR (existing or
    "ADR-required: <title>") in the last column.
============================================================ -->

